  "prompt": "How do I calculate mass of the moon using mass of the earth?",
  "response": "To calculate the mass of the Moon using the mass of the Earth, you need to know the ratio of their masses. The mass of the Moon is approximately 1/81 that of the Earth.\n\nGiven:\n- Mass of the Earth (M_earth) = \\( 5.972 \\times 10^{24} \\) kilograms\n\nThe mass of the Moon (M_moon) can be calculated using the ratio:\n\\[ M_{\\text{moon}} = \\frac{1}{81} \\times M_{\\text{earth}} \\]\n\nSo,\n\\[ M_{\\text{moon}} = \\frac{1}{81} \\times 5.972 \\times 10^{24} \\]\n\n\\[ M_{\\text{moon}} \\approx 7.37 \\times 10^{22} \\] kilograms\n\nTherefore, the mass of the Moon is approximately \\( 7.37 \\times 10^{22} \\) kilograms.",
